  "body": "It's probably not a big deal though for the \"naive\" strategy, still, bringing up here to get feedback.\r\n\r\n## Issue\r\nIf the attester reveal (i) their own unaggregated attestation at [Attesting](https://github.com/ethereum/eth2.0-specs/blob/dev/specs/phase0/validator.md#attesting) and (ii) their [`aggregate_and_proof`](https://github.com/ethereum/eth2.0-specs/blob/dev/specs/phase0/validator.md#broadcast-aggregate), the attacker can re-create a valid `aggregate_and_proof` by setting `aggregate_and_proof.aggregate` to any other aggregate that includes the aggregator's attestation.\r\n\r\nThe potential risk is that the attacker can do kind of dos attack on the global channel, and cause the honest aggregator has a bad reputation.\r\n\r\n## Proposed solution\r\n\r\nTo avoid the forge attack, the aggregator `A1` can:\r\n1. At [Attesting](https://github.com/ethereum/eth2.0-specs/blob/dev/specs/phase0/validator.md#attesting) stage, `A1` choose **not** to broadcast their unaggregated (individual) attestation `attestation_1`.\r\n2. `A1` only includes their unaggregated `attestation_1` in the `aggregate_and_proof` they created.\r\n\r\nHowever, the chance that `attestation_1` gets included in the block will be decreased since the *other* aggregators will not involve `attestation_1` to their aggregate.\r\n\r\np.s. if we update the aggregator logic, it's related to https://github.com/ethereum/eth2.0-APIs/pull/15/",
